Thus the invasions of the Gauls were of little historical importance. Nor is the reason of this difficult to see. The restless spirit of the Celtic nation, combined with their intolerance of the re- straint of any fixed politica] constitution, forbade them to settle down to reap the full advantage of any victory they might gain. Their expeditions were undertaken more for the sake of plunder than dominion. “Such qualities——those of good soldiers but bad citizens—explain the historical fact, that the Celts have shaken many states but founded none.''

C.-L1VY AND HIS HISTORY.

Titus Livius was born at Patavium (Padua) in B.C. 59, and lived till the fourth year of Tiberius, A.D. 17. &Vc have little or no information concern- ing his private life. The assertion that, in his youth, he studied to become an orator, is borne out by the eloquence and oratorical ability displayed in the numerous speeches incorporated in his writings.
